Of all the Enterprise Architecture perspectives, Application Architecture is the natural companion to Business Architecture. The sheer number of viewpoints you _could_ create for an application is staggering, but in the Stealth EA practice, we focus on the few that consistently prove their worth over time.
### [[Application Context Model]]

The Application Context Model is your foundation. This view explains who uses the application, how the application breaks down functionally, and what information flows between it and other internal or external applications. That functional decomposition becomes particularly valuable when you're working with the Value Stage Model and need to get down to the Business Capability Instance level of detail.
### [[Application Environments Model]]

Every application needs to live somewhere. Whether you're maintaining your own physical infrastructure or working with cloud vendors, you need to understand your production, development, testing, and any other environments that keep your application running. We all wish this level of architecture would auto-magically generate itself from the CMDB, but, as Maxwell Smart said, "Missed it by *that* much."
### [[Application Information Exchange Model]]

Every application view represents information exchanges in some form. At the Application Portfolio level, that might be nothing more than an ArchiMate Flow relationship. At the Application Context level, you should be getting down to the Application Interface level of detail. In any medium-sized enterprise, there are more layers to consider: integration buses bridging applications, platform applications with their own integration capabilities, and finally the level where you can document any transforms required along the way.
